            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers being ten, standing on a milk crate to reach the counter as his father showed him how to count the cash drawer. The worn bills smelled of masa and grilled onions. His father\u2019s calloused hand rested on his shoulder, a silent approval that felt heavier and more important than any A+ on a report card. It wasn't about the money; it was the first time he felt the weight of his family's trust, cementing a sense of responsibility that would define his entire life.\n\n2.\nThe hospital waiting room buzzed with a sterile, fluorescent hum. His mother was praying softly, and his unopened economics textbook felt absurdly hollow on his lap. He looked at his mother\u2019s tired, frightened face and thought of the restaurant\u2014the vendors, the payroll, the morning prep. The choice wasn\u2019t a choice at all; it was a simple, crushing calculation. He closed the textbook, the soft thud sealing his decision and shaping a future defined by duty over his own desires. This happened his sophomore year of college.\n\n3.\nHis first major project at the consulting firm was a logistical mess. He watched the Ivy League analysts whiteboard complex theories. Quietly, Mateo mapped it out like a week\u2019s supply order for the pupuseria\u2014vendors, timing, dependencies, contingency. He handed his simple flowchart to the senior partner. The partner\u2019s long silence, followed by a slow nod of understanding, was the moment Mateo realized his years by the plancha weren't a detour. They were his true, practical education, building a quiet competence that degrees couldn't teach.\n\n4.\nHe took Sofia on a tour of the SF State campus last fall, when she was fifteen. Standing in the student plaza, he saw a ghost of his 19-year-old self. He watched his daughter, vibrant and full of questions about her own future, and felt a fierce, protective pride. The ache of his own sacrificed path was completely overshadowed by the clear purpose that replaced it: ensuring her path would be wide open, with no exits required. This was his true bottom line.\n\n5.\nMost mornings on the J Church train, as it rattles past Dolores Park towards downtown, his history podcast will mention a place in Central America. He\u2019ll close his eyes for just a moment, picturing Mayan ruins or volcanic lakes. The brief, vivid daydream is a familiar ritual. It\u2019s a quiet acknowledgment of a life he hasn't yet lived, a heritage known only through stories. This flicker of melancholy sharpens his resolve for Sofia, and fuels a small, patient hope for his own future."
